"""Practical engineering recipes — how-to for common tasks across domains."""
LESSONS=[
    ('How do I deploy a Python web app?','Steps: (1) pin deps in requirements.txt or pyproject.toml + lockfile. (2) write Dockerfile (slim base, install deps, copy code, run with gunicorn/uvicorn). (3) test locally. (4) push to registry (Docker Hub, ECR, GHCR). (5) deploy via platform (Railway, Render, Fly.io for easy; ECS/Kubernetes/Cloud Run for more control). (6) configure secrets via env vars. (7) health checks + monitoring + logs.'),
    ('How do I add HTTPS to my site?','Easiest: use a hosting platform (Vercel, Netlify, Cloudflare Pages) — automatic. Self-hosted: Caddy is simplest (auto Let\'s Encrypt). Nginx + Certbot also works (free certs, auto-renewal). For internal services: mTLS or private CA. Never run plain HTTP for anything user-facing in 2025.'),
    ('How do I implement search in an app?','Three levels of complexity. Simple: SQL LIKE/ILIKE for small datasets. Better: Postgres full-text search (tsvector, GIN index) — built-in, no extra infra. Best: Elasticsearch / Meilisearch / Typesense for huge data + relevance scoring + facets + typos. Modern: embedding-based semantic search (vector DB) for "meaning-based" queries. Hybrid (keyword + semantic) often wins.'),
    ('How do I handle user uploads?','(1) validate type + size CLIENT-side (UX) AND server-side (security). (2) store in object storage (S3, R2, B2), not local disk. (3) generate signed upload URLs (client uploads directly to bucket, bypassing your server). (4) virus scan if user-facing (ClamAV, Cloudflare). (5) serve via CDN with image resizing on-the-fly (Cloudinary, Imgix, or self-hosted with sharp).'),
    ('How do I implement authentication for a web app?','Start with managed: Auth0, Clerk, Supabase Auth, Firebase Auth — handle hard parts (password reset, OAuth, MFA, security audits). DIY only if necessary: bcrypt/argon2 for passwords, sessions in cookies (HttpOnly + Secure + SameSite), refresh+access token rotation if API-based, OAuth providers for social login. Test thoroughly; auth bugs are catastrophic.'),
    ('How do I send transactional emails reliably?','Use a transactional email service: SendGrid, Postmark, Resend, AWS SES. Don\'t roll your own SMTP — deliverability is a science. Set up: SPF + DKIM + DMARC records (your DNS), warmup new domain gradually, use a dedicated subdomain, monitor bounce/complaint rates. Templates with personalization. Idempotency on send (don\'t spam users on retries).'),
    ('How do I add a background job queue?','For Python: Celery (mature, RabbitMQ/Redis backed), Dramatiq (simpler), RQ (Redis Queue, very simple), arq (async-native). Pattern: producer pushes job to queue; workers pull + process; results stored or notified. Idempotent job design — retries WILL happen. Dead letter queue for repeatedly failing jobs.'),
    ('How do I add scheduled tasks (cron jobs) to a web app?','Don\'t use system cron in container apps (containers restart). Options: (1) cloud scheduler (Cloud Scheduler, EventBridge, GitHub Actions cron) → HTTP webhook to your app. (2) library inside app (APScheduler, Celery beat). (3) sidecar service. For periodic + idempotent jobs, cloud scheduler is cleanest.'),
    ('How do I avoid [REDACTED]?','NEVER concatenate user input into SQL. ALWAYS use parameterized queries (placeholders): `cursor.execute("SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?", (user_id,))`. ORMs do this for you. Edge cases: identifiers (table/column names) can\'t be parameterized — whitelist them against a fixed set. Same for ORDER BY direction. Never trust user input.'),
    ('How do I implement caching properly?','Identify hot reads. Add cache layer (Redis, Memcached, in-process LRU). Pattern: check cache → miss → compute → store with TTL → return. Invalidation: TTL OR explicit on write. Cache stampede protection: lock or stale-while-revalidate. Never cache responses with PII without scoping per user. Monitor hit rate.'),
    ('How do I implement rate limiting?','Use API gateway (Cloudflare, AWS API Gateway, Nginx) if possible — closer to client. App-level: token bucket via Redis (atomic INCR + EXPIRE). Per-user OR per-IP OR per-API-key. Return 429 with Retry-After header. Whitelist trusted internal IPs. Stricter limits on expensive endpoints (search, AI).'),
    ('How do I add observability to a new service?','Day 1 essentials: (1) structured logs with request_id + level. (2) metric endpoint (/metrics, Prometheus format). (3) tracing via OpenTelemetry. (4) health endpoint (/health for liveness, /ready for readiness). (5) alert on SLO burn rate (not raw error count). Don\'t go observability-overkill — start with the basics + add as you learn what you need.'),
    ('How do I roll back a bad deploy?','Best: have AUTOMATIC rollback. Trigger on error rate spike or health check fail. Manual rollback: keep previous image tag, redeploy. For DB migrations: never delete columns immediately (multi-step: deploy code that ignores → migrate to drop → deploy code that no longer references). Never edit prod data manually except in emergencies (and document).'),
    ('How do I do database migrations safely?','(1) test in staging with production-like data. (2) backward-compatible schema changes (add column nullable, deploy code, then make NOT NULL in next migration). (3) for big tables: use online schema change tools (pt-online-schema-change MySQL, pg-online MySQL). (4) take a backup. (5) deploy during low-traffic. (6) have rollback plan tested. Tools: Alembic (Python), Flyway, Liquibase, Atlas.'),
    ('How do I A/B test a feature?','Use a flag service (LaunchDarkly, GrowthBook, Statsig) or hand-roll. Bucket users deterministically (hash(user_id) % N). Track conversion + significance properly (sequential testing, not peeking). Cap A/B durations + min sample sizes. Don\'t run too many tests at once (interaction effects). Always have an off switch.'),
    ('How do I detect memory leaks in production?','Watch RSS over time per process. Alert on sustained growth. To diagnose: (1) tracemalloc / heap snapshots from running process. (2) restart process periodically as workaround while investigating. (3) check for unbounded caches, queues, thread-local storage. (4) cross-reference with deploys — when did it start?'),
    ('How do I scale reads?','(1) cache hot reads (Redis / Memcached / in-process). (2) read replicas — serve queries from replicas, writes to primary. (3) denormalize for query speed (materialized views). (4) CDN for static content. (5) move expensive reads to background pre-compute. (6) sharding LAST resort — adds complexity. Most apps fit on one big Postgres for years.'),
    ('How do I scale writes?','(1) batch — combine multiple writes into one. (2) async queue — accept request fast, write in background. (3) write-through cache. (4) partition / shard if necessary (last resort). (5) consider event sourcing — append-only log scales better than mutate-in-place. (6) consider purpose-built stores for hot data (Redis for counters).'),
    ('How do I handle large file uploads?','Multipart upload: client splits into chunks, uploads in parallel, server stitches. S3 + signed URLs handle this natively (5MB chunks). Browser: tus.io protocol for resumable. For >100MB: ALWAYS resumable + chunked + parallel. Show progress. Validate on server (size, content-type, virus scan).'),
    ('How do I keep secrets out of git?','(1) .gitignore .env files. (2) pre-commit hook checking for secrets (gitleaks, trufflehog). (3) rotate any secret accidentally committed (history is forever). (4) store in secret manager (Vault, AWS Secrets Manager, Doppler) not env files in repo. (5) for CI: platform secrets (GitHub Secrets) — never echo in logs.'),
    ('How do I migrate from sync to async Python?','Identify I/O hot spots. Convert one path at a time: (1) make the leaf I/O async (replace requests with httpx, sync DB with asyncpg). (2) propagate async upward through callers. (3) replace ThreadPoolExecutor with asyncio.to_thread for remaining blocking calls. Don\'t convert CPU-bound work — use multiprocessing. Test concurrent paths thoroughly — async bugs are subtle.'),
    ('How do I migrate from REST to GraphQL?','Don\'t replace — augment. Add GraphQL endpoint as a thin layer over existing REST/RPC backends. Resolvers call existing services. Iteratively move hot client queries to GraphQL. Eventually decide: keep both, or sunset REST. Pitfalls: N+1 queries (use DataLoader), unbounded depth (limit), unbounded list size (paginate), expensive queries (cost analysis).'),
    ('How do I add internationalization (i18n)?','Externalize strings to translation files (JSON, YAML, gettext .po). Use library: react-i18next (React), Django i18n, Rails I18n, ICU MessageFormat for plural rules. Pluralization is harder than translation — different languages have different rules. Date/number formatting via Intl APIs (browser native). Right-to-left languages need CSS changes too.'),
    ('How do I make my service handle 10x traffic suddenly?','Plan ahead: (1) load test BEFORE the launch. (2) auto-scaling configured + tested (don\'t learn it doesn\'t work during the surge). (3) cache hot reads at every layer (CDN, app cache, DB cache). (4) async non-critical work. (5) graceful degradation paths (turn off recommendations if recs service overloaded). (6) circuit breakers + bulkheads. (7) on-call ready with runbooks.'),
]
